description: From French insipide, from Latin īnsipidus (“tasteless”), from in- (“not”) + sapidus (“savory”). In some senses, perhaps influenced by insipient (“unwise, foolish, stupid”).

adjectives.description: insipid (comparative more insipid, superlative most insipid)

examples: The diners were disappointed with the plain, insipid soup they were served.
Synonyms: boring, vacuous, dull, bland, characterless, colourless
The textbook had a most insipid presentation of the controversy.
